        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Target of Opportunity: In order to measure the distribution of extended source species towards a comet, an estimate of the line intensity is needed, as well as the approximate size of the apparition.  We have determined abundance estimates from a active comet at Rh~1AU and Delta~1AU with a Q(H2O) ~ 1e29 s-1.  Our science program will be activated if these approximate conditions (both comet activity and approximate location) are met, with a reaction time of a few days to a few weeks.  These triggers allow for apparitions of dynamically new objects and/or outbursts from known periodic comets.  Estimates of line intensities are highly uncertain given the molecular diversity of comets.  However, we anticipate with our trigger conditions to obtain detections comparable to those we measured in F6/Lemmon and Q2/Lovejoy at this Band.  The science goals can be achieved in any array configuration from C36-1 to C36-5 within the time requested, 2 mJy km/s, by reaching reasonable S/N in CO, the strongest lines of CH3OH, HCN, and the strongest line of H2CO.  Once a target is selected that fulfills our trigger, we will provide an ephemeris from JPL/Horizons.

Sensitivity Requirements: Based on these limitations, estimates of each lines flux have been made and a sensitivity requirement was constrained to 5sigma for the weakest CH3OH line in the band to ensure a proper temperature analysis of the coma.  This will also allow for the detection (&gt;=6sigma) of CO, H2CO, and HCN lines in each frequency setting.  

Table 1: Predicted signals for Cycle 3 for a ToO comet with Q(H2O) ~ 1e29 s-1, Rh~1 AU and Delta~1 AU.  The requested sensitivity (2mJy km/s) was determined at 5sigma for the weakest CH3OH line in the bands (after subtracting the 30% losses due to incomplete sampling of the Fourier plane), to ensure detections of all observable lines and derive the temperature of the gas during each observation.
